      "text": "\n\n\n0.0003 BTC (or 30,000 satoshis) for a standard Bitcoin transfer is definitely on the higher side, but it does not necessarily mean there is something wrong with your wallet configuration or that your security is compromised. \n\nHere is a breakdown of why you might have paid that amount and what you should check in your wallet settings:\n\n### 1. Network Congestion (The Fee Market)\nBitcoin transaction fees are not based on the dollar value of the transfer, but rather on the physical data size of the transaction (measured in virtual bytes, or vBytes) and the current demand for block space.\n* A typical simple transaction is around **140 to 200 vBytes**.\n* If you paid 30,000 satoshis for a 150 vByte transaction, you paid a fee rate of roughly **200 sats/vByte**. \nDuring times of high network congestion (such as heavy market volatility or surges in network activity), a rate of 100 to 300+ sats/vByte is entirely normal to get a transaction confirmed quickly. \n\n### 2. Transaction Size (UTXOs)\nIf you receive a lot of small payments to your wallet (like daily mining payouts or smaller DCA purchases) and then send a larger amount out, your wallet has to combine all those small inputs (UTXOs) to create the outgoing transaction. Combining many inputs makes the data size of the transaction much larger.\n* If your transaction size was actually 1,000 vBytes because it consolidated several inputs, then 30,000 sats equates to just **30 sats/vByte**. This is a very standard, moderate fee rate.\n\n### 3. Wallet Fee Settings\nMost modern wallets have built-in fee estimators. If the network was only moderately busy but you still paid 200 sats/vB, your wallet configuration might be set too aggressively. \n* **Priority Settings:** Check your wallet’s settings to see if your default transaction speed is set to \"High Priority\" or \"Fastest.\" This will automatically bid the highest current fee rate to ensure inclusion in the very next block.\n* **Dynamic vs. Custom Fees:** Many wallets allow you to switch from \"Dynamic\" estimation to \"Custom\" fees. \n\n### What You Should Do Moving Forward:\nYou do not need to be worried about the integrity of your wallet. However, to avoid overpaying in the future, you should:\n1. **Check the Mempool:** Before sending a transaction, check a block explorer like[mempool.space](https://mempool.space) to see current network fee rates.\n2. **Use Custom Fees:** If you are not in a rush, select a custom fee rate in your wallet. Paying a lower rate (e.g., 10–20 sats/vByte instead of 200) might mean waiting a few hours for confirmation, but it will save you a lot of money.\n3. **Use SegWit/Taproot:** Ensure your wallet is using Native SegWit (addresses starting with `bc1q`) or Taproot (`bc1p`) addresses, as these make the transaction data size smaller and inherently lower your fees.",
